	<td width="98%">

		<table width="100%">
		<tr>
			<td>
				<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="3"><b>    <B>* Everlore's Guide to Dyeing Armor</B></b></font>
					<br>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">
					<b><A href="mailto:Hondo@obsidian-tech.com">Korupter (E-Marr)</a> | 
		            11/13/2000 3:42:49 PM</b></font></p>
		         <a href="guides.asp">
		         <font face="verdana" size="2">Return to guide listing.</font></a>
					
					<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="2"><p><font face="Verdana">Introduction</font></p>
<p><font face="Verdana" size="2">This Section is strictly dedicated to learning
the art of dyeing and applying the dyes. I have researched this art fairly well
but due to it being such a new art some of the information may be wrong. If
there is anything you see wrong with this chart or that it needs feel free to
send me a e-mail at <a href="mailto:Hondo@obsidian-tech.com">Korupter (E-Marr)</a>.</font></p>
<p><font face="Verdana">Everlore's Guide to Dyeing</font></p>
<ul>
  <li><font face="Verdana"><b><a href="http://www.everlore.com/skills/default.asp?mode=5&id=548">Everlore's
    Guide to General Blacksmithing</a></b></font></li>
  <li><font face="Verdana"><b><a href="http://www.everlore.com/guides.asp?ID=12760">Everlore's
    Guide to General/Advance Blacksmithing</a></b></font></li>
</ul>
<p><font face="Verdana">Everlore's First Step for Making Dye</font></p>
<p><font face="Verdana" size="2">Dyes Before you can even start to do anything
you need to have some supplies. Must realize that only Fine Steel Plate Armor can be
dyed. Now lets get started. Here are some of the Supplies needed.</font></p>
<ul>
  <li><font face="Verdana" size="2">Empty Vials, Flask of Water, Jars of Acid,
    Jars of Lacquer, Medium Clay Jars, Resin.</font></li>
</ul>
<p><font face="Verdana" size="2">Some of the items used here have to to be
bought from a vendor or it will not work. Empty Vials, Resin, Jar of Acid, Jar
of Lacquer can only be purchased at 2 places. One place is the one of the
vendors inside one of the windmills in Steamfont. The second place is inside
High Hold Keep heading down towards the pickclaw mines near the bank. The 
Empty Vials must be bought here. Once you have these you can can start with the
dyes.</font></p>
<p><font face="Verdana" size="2">Hopefully you know some Shamans or Rogues
because you will need there help and skills. If not you can always ask or pay to
have someone make the coloring for you. Once you get one you will need to give
them the the raw material you are going to extract the color from. Along with
that they need to be given a Empty Vial and a Flask of Water. Make sure there is
skill is above 40 to be sure or you might lose your materials if he fails. he
then will place all those components in a Alchemist Bag or a Mortar and Pestle.
The results are you get a new extract. Here are some of the extracts that have
been discovered.</font></p>
<ul>
  <li><font face="Verdana" size="2">Permafrost Crystals</font></li>
  <li><font face="Verdana" size="2">Jack`o`Lantern Fungus</font></li>
  <li><font face="Verdana" size="2">Sarcoscypha Fungus</font></li>
  <li><font face="Verdana" size="2">Evergreen Leaves</font></li>
  <li><font face="Verdana" size="2">Iron Oxide</font></li>
  <li><font face="Verdana" size="2">Charcoal</font></li>
  <li><font face="Verdana" size="2">Russet Oxide</font></li>
</ul>
<p><font face="Verdana" size="2">These will be listed for the colors they make
on the chart below.</font></p>
<p> </p>
<p><font face="Verdana" size="2">To finish making the dye or a dye you can use
you have to mix the extract you just had the Rogue or Shaman make inside a a
Medium Jar along with either one two or three Resins to vary the colors of the
dye. You will need to have 1 Medium Jar for each finished dye or piece of armor
you plan to dye because when you use a Jar they are Expendable. Here is a list
of the the shades of colors you will get when using the resins.</font></p>
<ul>
  <li><font face="Verdana" size="2">1 resin will make a light shade color</font></li>
  <li><font face="Verdana" size="2">2 resins will make a basic shade of the
    color</font></li>
  <li><font face="Verdana" size="2">3 resin will make a dark shade of the color</font></li>
</ul>
<p><font face="Verdana" size="2">Now that you have the dye ready to work into
the armor you are prepared to actually start dyeing armors now. This process
takes place at any general forge. Now all you have to do now is to put your dye
that you have made into the forge along with a Jar of Lacquer,a Jar of Acid, and
the Fine Plate you wish to dye. Ding you have now finished dyeing your armor.</font></p>
<p align="center"><b>Everlore's Color Chart</b></p>
<p align="center"><font face="Martel" size="6">Dyes and Colors Chart</font></p>
<table border="1" width="100%" height="120">
  <tr>
    <td width="15%" height="18"><b><font face="Verdana">Color:</font></b></td>
    <td width="36%" height="18"><b><font face="Verdana">Ingredient:</font></b></td>
    <td width="49%" height="18"><b><font face="Verdana">Item Found:</font></b></td>
  </tr>
