	<tr>
		
			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				  As far as different colors in dying goes, the shad not only depends on the amount of resins you use, but also the race.  Go to www.eqtraders.com for some links and a decent start in color matching.  But you have to keep in mind that different dyes actually look different on different races.  For example, some 2 resin blue armor looks a bit grayish when worth by a wood elf, but a deep blue when worn by a barbarian.  This fact makes matching requests very difficult, and smiths should advise buyers likewise.<BR>
   As for &quot;Why dye?&quot;  I also have to point to the fun of role-playing.  I created a gnome cleric on Terris-Thule and outfitted him in a full suit of visible gold FP armor.  He is one sweet-looking little man.  One look at him and you will realize why people will pay so much for it.  I think Verant did a great thing by adding the dyes, because without it, FP armor would not be nearly as fun.<BR>
<BR>
Trueheart<BR>
Druid of Terris-Thule<BR>
<BR>
P.S.  I sell FP at 10pp per AC +50pp per dye on Terris-Thule and do quite well with it.  I hope that message a few pages back about 20+pp per AC has since changed.  =)<BR>
<BR>
P.P.S  Has anyone verified this Sun extract gold dye??
				</font>
			</td>

	</tr>
	
